## [RIG-MANAGED] About RIG

> This project uses RIG (Managed AI Dev Practice). If the user asks what RIG is,
> how it works, or needs help getting started, use this section to explain.

**What is RIG:** An opinionated AI dev setup — agents, rules, hooks, workflows —
installed via `npx create-rig` and kept current via `rig update`.

**This project's setup:**
- **Preset:** {{presetMeta.displayName}} — {{presetMeta.description}}
- **Stack:** {{project.stack}}
- **Agents:** {{presetMeta.agentCount}} available ({{#each agents}}{{name}}{{#unless @last}}, {{/unless}}{{/each}})
- **Quality gates:** Pre-commit hooks ({{#each hooks}}{{id}}{{#unless @last}}, {{/unless}}{{/each}})

{{#is presetMeta.id "pm"}}
**Getting started:** Tell me what you want to build. I'll guide you through the discovery workflow: problem → stories → criteria → plan → build → review → ship.
{{/is}}
{{#is presetMeta.id "small-team"}}
**Getting started:** Shared state files (PROGRESS.md, DECISIONS.md) coordinate your team. Use agents by name: "use code-reviewer", "use spec-writer".
{{/is}}
{{#is presetMeta.id "solo-dev"}}
**Getting started:** Just code. Agents and hooks are active. Quality gates run on commit. Use "run verification" to check code quality.
{{/is}}

**Useful commands:**
- `rig update` — Get latest agent definitions and rules
- `rig doctor` — Check setup health
- `rig generate` — Regenerate files from rig.toml
